TY  - JOUR
AU  - Lewellen, Jonathan
T1  - Momentum and Autocorrelation in Stock Returns
PY  - 2002
Y1  - 2002/01/02
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/15.2.533
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 15
IS  - 2
SP  - 533
EP  - 564
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - This article studies momentum in stock returns, focusing on the role of industry, size, and book-to-market (B/M) factors. Size and B/M portfolios exhibit momentum as strong as that in individual stocks and industries. The size and B/M portfolios are well diversified, so momentum cannot be attributed to firm- or industry-specific returns. Further, industry, size, and B/M portfolios are negatively autocorrelated and cross-serially correlated over intermediate horizons. The evidence suggests that stocks covary “too strongly” with each other. I argue that excess covariance, not underreaction, explains momentum in the portfolios.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/15.2.533
ER  - 



